Family -  Happy Sunday! We are a week into the new year... lots of us have big goals, big things we are hoping to be better at, I am a huge advocate for growth, for discipline, for dedication.. however, I know that trying to change it ALL at once never pans out. 

That is why I want to share a little advise on how I like to tackle new goals. 

1. I break them down into smaller, attainable wins that I can do on a daily basis, and most importantly with consistency. Though it may take longer than I'd like, I know this strategy will help me develop the mental fortitude to reach the big wins. 

2. I surround myself with supportive people that will lift me up in my new personal goal or business venture .. this doesn't always mean I will find these people in my family or within my current friend group, this means I proactively pursue communities of people that are successful in the arena I am looking to tackle. The @kreaturesofhabit community we are building is there for this. 
 
3. Use the "one at a time" approach - DO NOT try to change your whole existence in a day.. Smaller steps, longer distances... 

4. Be kind to myself, if I fall, I don't judge, all I have to do is get back up and that's success. 

5. When it comes to my personal wellness, I have come to learn that it's a long game... everything takes time.. Especially when it comes to fitness and nutrition. 

If you need a change or want to step up your nutritional game... Try MEAL ONE as an amazing first step, it's delicious, incredibly clean ingredients, so so so easy to make and is a full meal that keep you satiated for hours. .

#ad When training for a competition, every data point counts. And the more you know about your performance, the better an edge you have on progressing. I like to pay attention to a lot of things when training: my heart rate, which zone I’m in and for how long, how many calories I burn to help guide my nutritional decisions, and how well I’m sleeping on a daily basis. My Galaxy Watch5 Pro helps inform me of all of these data points, and the best part is that it’s all on my wrist..
The real power of journaling: there’s a lesson in everything you do.

#ad Nutrition is as important for competition training as the training itself. I think of it like a car — the car may look strong, sleek, and fast, but if there’s no fuel in the tank, or the wrong kind of fuel, the car won’t perform, bottom line. My Galaxy Watch5 Pro guides me in making educated decisions for my nutritional planning. In the BIA feature I can see everything from my basal metabolic rate (how many calories I burn daily just breathing) as well as how many calories I burn in a workout. Based on my goals, I’m then able to take that information and gauge how many calories I need to ingest daily to maintain and/or increase for performance. This tool is also incredibly helpful for when I’m trying to shed some body fat. It works both ways. For me, post-workout nutrition is very important. If I know I just burned 650 calories, I‘ll want to eat roughly 650 after the workout to maintain my body composition.

Drawing boundaries for yourself, not only with your parents or with your significant other, but with your time.

I block out time throughout the day for my fitness, for my mindfulness.

I draw these very, very strict, hard boundaries for myself so that I know exactly what I've got to do and it helps me feel freedom.

It's that discipline = freedom component.

Secondly, movement.

Movement is necessary for my mental and physical health.

I have to move, I have to work out. It's super duper important for me.

Sometimes that workout is just getting 10,000 steps a day.

Sometimes it's yoga today, and other times it's a really hard, intense strength training or CrossFit workout.

Movement is everything for me.

Movement is my mental health, medicine.

And then of course, mindfulness for me is very, very important.

That includes prayer, meditation, journaling, reading, all the stuff that I like to incorporate into my morning routine is what I consider mindfulness.

I like to have those three things: movement, mindfulness and boundaries.

If you stick to those three things you will be healthy mentally, physically and spiritually.
